1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with coding methods for the additive white Gaussian noise channel with average codeword power constraint, which is a classic problem in information theory. 
2. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper discusses the decoding of sparse superpositions using least squares, which involves computational complexity. 
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper may be relevant to the design of communication protocols for social and information networks. 
4. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper may be relevant to the design of coding schemes for wireless communication networks. 
5. cs.LG (Machine Learning) - The paper may be relevant to the use of sparse superpositions in machine learning applications.
